Hey Lila,

If you=E2=80=99re creating an app or website with search functionality,
then you know at some point, someone is going to end up searching
for something that doesn=E2=80=99t return any results.

Here=E2=80=99s a bad way to design that screen. Can you count the
problems?

=E2=80=8B
Off the top of my head:

* Message feels really unhelpful
* Message is full of jargon ("query", "records")
* It's really subtle that I have a filter applied

But rather than brainstorm a bunch of random possible issues,
let's talk about a single question that will solve all of these
design problems.

The question is this: if the user=E2=80=99s search didn=E2=80=99t return an=
y
results, why not?

Sure, =E2=80=9Cthey searched for something that doesn=E2=80=99t exist=E2=80=
=9D might be a
reason. But again: why?

* Because they entered a typo
* Because our database is legitimately missing something
* Because they don=E2=80=99t understand the types of things they can
search for
* Because they forgot that they had a filter applied

Let's address these one at a time and see where we end up.

1/ Because they entered a typo

If the user made a typo, we can offer =E2=80=9Cfuzzy matching=E2=80=9D. Thi=
nk how
Google will sometimes say, e.g. =E2=80=9CDid you mean entropy?=E2=80=9D or =
some
such.

=E2=80=8B
But that=E2=80=99s not an issue with this particular example, so we'll
make a mental note of how we'd solve it and move on =F0=9F=99=82

2/ Because our database is legitimately missing something

If our database is missing something, users should be able to
request that we add it.

We've also corrected the user-blaming language =F0=9F=91=8D
That's easy enough! A contact link will do the trick. Note: this
also totally changes the vibe of the error message.

OLD VIBE: your question was bad.

NEW VIBE: sorry we couldn't find any results, which is probably
our fault, so here's a way to reach us personally to help us fix
it =F0=9F=A4=97

Much better, in my opinion. Moving on.

3/ Because they don=E2=80=99t understand the types of things they can
search for

If users don=E2=80=99t understand what they can search for, let=E2=80=99s s=
how
some of our most popular equations. Not only are most popular
equations most likely to be useful for the average user, it=E2=80=99s
also a great way to Teach By Example (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/4zuq65w5k0heh789oqtx/3ohphkhqz96vdmar/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnVpLmRlc2lnbi9ibG9nLzQtcnVsZXMtaW50dWl0aXZlLXV4Lmh0bWwjNC10ZW=
FjaC1ieS1leGFtcGxl
).

=E2=80=8B
It's not perfect, but it will definitely make life better for
some newer users.

4/ Because they forgot that they had a filter applied

If users forgot about a filter, let=E2=80=99s make it really visually
obvious when there=E2=80=99s one applied.

=E2=80=8B
Taken together, we=E2=80=99ve got a full-on redesign of this page just
from asking one question! Not bad.

=E2=80=8B
This example was featured in the newly re-recorded video for
Designing Multi-State Screens, the lesson in Learn UI Design (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/4zuq65w5k0heh789oqtx/wnh2hghrgv98o2h7/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9sZWFybnVpLmRlc2lnbi8=3D
) in which I talk about the most common types of "alternate
states" UI designers have to account for:

* Loading states
* Error states
* Initial/data-less states
* And more

But errors are fairly complex, and I also address them thoroughly
in Learn UX Design (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/4zuq65w5k0heh789oqtx/8ghqhohg9pek57bk/aHR=
